From 525f12f295e165175f7cc29ca2073d9d68ee879b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 10:40:51 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 5/7] Let administrators state IO weights on BFQ's own scale

IOWeight= is a deeply unintuitive knob on any node using BFQ, which is the
only scheduler most deployments have that implements proportional IO
control at all.

BFQ keeps its weight in io.bfq.weight on a 1..1000 scale and does not read
io.weight -- that file belongs to the iocost controller, inert unless
io.cost.model/io.cost.qos are configured. systemd bridges the gap by
deriving io.bfq.weight from IOWeight, compressing 100..10000 into
100..1000. Ratios above the default therefore shrink by ~11x: IOWeight=1000
yields io.bfq.weight=181, i.e. 1.81x against a default sibling rather than
the 10x it reads like, and a genuine 5x needs IOWeight=4500. Nothing
surfaces this -- io.weight faithfully reads back the ineffective number
that was written.

Add io_bfq_weight / WINGS_CG_IO_BFQ_WEIGHT stating the weight on BFQ's
scale, converted to the equivalent IOWeight and applied as an ordinary
systemd property. systemd's divisor is exactly 1/11, so the round trip is
exact for every weight in 1..1000. Writing io.bfq.weight directly would be
the obvious alternative and is a trap: systemd re-derives that file from
IOWeight whenever it re-applies the unit's IO settings, silently clobbering
the raw value -- the same class of bug this package exists to avoid.

The two spellings drive one property and are mutually exclusive; setting
both is reported rather than resolved by guessing. Slice property logs now
name the derived io.bfq.weight so the effective weight is visible without
knowing the mapping exists.

Expected values verified against a live systemd 257 / Linux 7.0 node.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
